segments.text: Austin, picking up where we left off in the interview with Davis Ford.
And let's start by your describing.
One this morning, you don't have to hear this one, you'll get it when they record it.
From Holtz, is that his name?
Yeah.
Yeah.
He's going to record it.
I gave her the ring and she gave me the finger.
Yeah.

Of course, circa 55 to 59 was my era there, and I was from West Texas, so I obviously couldn't go back to Lubbock very frequently, so my roommates and my Aggie colleagues and I would come primarily to Austin, Dallas, and Houston to have our social life.
Of those three, I must admit that Austin was our favorite.
It seems like that the University of Texas coeds kind of got tired of the attorney boys, and the Aggies were kind of a breath of fresh air, so my roommate
and dear friends at that time, and I had girlfriends in Austin, so we would make the trek here, this was my junior and senior year when we had more freedom, make the trek on a regular basis.
Virtually every weekend we were in Austin.
And what, Carlota?
No, just two of us on that particular occasion, because we had girlfriends who also were friends with each other, so it was just a real night.
It made, after two years of kind of social isolation, we all of a sudden really started enjoying the fruition of social life in college our junior and senior year.
Right, but now back in Brown College Station, if you and
Some of your friends want to just go off campus and have a good time.
Where'd y'all go?
Well, uh, the clay pits, obviously.
It's a swimming hole.
And what'd y'all do at the clay pits?
Well, we just used to go out there, and, uh, of course, I was, uh, a little serious, too, because I didn't drink much beer, but my colleagues would go out there and drink beer and jump in the water.
Uh, sometimes with girlfriends, sometimes not.
That was, that was my version.
Uh, Brian and Charlie's station were going to stay out at that time.
Uh, and this really wasn't too much to do.
I'd go down to Brian's and say, put this out right now.
He came in, let it go just a little.
This is a second start on the 18th of September.
Austin with Davis Ford.
Disregard everything on this tape prior to this point because it will sound amusing.
We began this morning, and I was asking you to describe the community of College Station when you were a student and what you and your fellow Aggies in the 50s
What did you all do for fun?
Where did you go?
Not too much to do in College Station or Bryan.
As I mentioned previously, the clay pits were kind of the place to hang out.
Just old sand borough area and had some water in it.
So we'd go out there and swim and drink a little beer.
And that was one place.
Other than that, it was pretty mundane.
There were no particular places that we enjoyed going there that I can recall an immediate area.
Now you mentioned earlier about coming to Austin, you and some other friends.
Was that typical?
Were there a number of students who went?
I think that the points of light around where we'd spend our weekends would be Austin, Dallas, Houston, those three places, at least the crowds that I ran in.
And I think of those three, my favorite was certainly Austin.
My roommate and I, my junior and senior year, were dating University of Texas girls, and Austin was a fun place to come, and that was our favorite habitat.
Now, other of my colleagues, we might go to Dallas or Houston or maybe Denton, but my favorite place, including a lot of my good friends, was to come down here to Austin.
On Austin, on a weekend, if you and a date went out,
Did anybody tease an Aggie or make fun of an Aggie here in Austin?
Oh yeah, sure.
Was it good nature?
Oh, it was good nature.

I had some good personal friends who were at UT and we ragged each other pretty hard, but it was, they were mostly fraternity guys, but now when I was a freshman we were kind of looked down upon because we were young looking and had shaved heads, but when we got to become junior and seniors we were obviously more sophisticated in the world and
I think innately we considered ourselves to be a little superior to the fraternity boys, but it was all good fun.
When you came over here, did you wear uniforms?
No, no.
I assumed that you didn't wear a uniform.

As I recall, Haskell, the regs at that time and the corps, you could take a uniform off once you were 15 miles outside of town or something like that, outside of Bryant College Station, off the campus.
So we'd leave in our uniforms and then immediately change to civilian clothes once we got to that limit.
Now, was it common to have a car then?
Very uncommon.
I didn't have a car in my senior year.
So you doubled up with somebody who had a car, or you hitchhiked?
That's right.
Now, my freshman and sophomore year, I'd come to Austin quite a bit, and I'd put my uniform on because it was so easy to get a ride.
So I would hitchhike a lot my freshman year.
Not so much my sophomore and junior years.
I always had a friend who had a car, and then I had a car my senior year.
If you were going to hitchhike from the campus to Austin, where did you go to start that?
Right across the railroad by the vet school, where we normally start.
And was it common to get a ride all the way?
Oh, yeah.
It was easy.
It was real easy.
Did you hold up a sign or anything?
No.
Or just your thumb?
Just your thumb.
Sometimes you might go to Bastrop and change cars and get on into Austin.
It was never a problem back in 55, 56.
Did you or anybody else you know of ever have an unfortunate incident hitchhiking?
Very unusual.
Back in those days, it was a safe thing to do.
Now, the hitchhiker probably has as much to fear as the one who picks up the hitchhiker.
But I don't recall of any incident.
It was so common, it was just...
It was a nice way to do it.
All right, now, so when you're leaving Austin to go back to College Station, where did you catch the ride?
Out on 290, right outside of Austin.
My grandparents lived here, and they'd take me out to 290, and I'd be out there.
No time at all, you'd get a ride.
Let's see, was there bus service in Bryan College Station then?
You know, even then, from Austin, it was very, you had to go to Waco and change or something.
There was not a way to go.
But then in town, was there a municipal bus?
Could you ride that?
Oh, sure.
And where did you catch that bus?
Well, they had a center location in town that kind of had a radial effect in all parts of Austin.
No, no, no, in Bryan College Station.
Oh, in Bryan College Station?
Was there a municipal bus then?
Oh, no, no, none.
I'm sorry, we're just talking about Austin.
None whatsoever that I recall in Bryan College Station.
Let's see, and let's recapture your thoughts about Lupo and Pinky as people and what their role was in the life of the campus.
You were asking me about the real visible characters that we had on campus back in those days, and I recited that my freshman year,
Bear Bryant was a coach in 1955 that I remember pinky downs leading the yells at the Grove.
I believe that he passed away shortly thereafter, probably during my tenure at A&M.
I don't remember the exact date, but he was certainly a legend.
And the second was Lupo.
We're getting ready to talk about Lupo and other characters.
He, I remember...
When I first came on the campus in 1955, Lupo had a very prominent place there right next to the campus.
And he was advertised 50% off.
And of course, we never believed any of that.
But I think Lupo was one of the few marketing people I've ever seen, retailers, that actually gave you 50% off, because we'd compare prices.
And he always seemed to be the lowest.
But he was very philanthropic.
He helped out freshmen.
He was just a great man.
And I tracked him all the way through past graduation.
I think he finally passed away just, what, five or ten years ago.
So he was quite an institution.
He was a very unselfish person.
And he was good friends with Tiger Teague and Earl Rudder, so that kind of helped him.
Pinky?
No, Lupo.
No, no, no.
Describe Pinky.
Oh, Pinky?
What you saw of him.
Well, he's a little bitty guy, and his suits always seemed too big for him.
I don't really know much about his history.
I'd read about him in a book that was written on Texas A&M, I believe back in 1950 or 51.
But where did you see him and how did you encounter him?
Yeah, well he'd be around the campus, but also I'd see him at Yale practice back in 55, 56.
And Bear Bryant, describe him during your years.
You know, Bear Bryant is kind of interesting.
I went to school with, and still good friends with him, Charlie Milstead,
Told me a lot of Bear Bryant stories.
Also, my wife was from Bryant and used to date some of the Bear Bryant football players.
So I got a lot of stories about him.
I'd see him from time to time around the MSC.
At that time, we thought he was old, mean-looking, but at that time he was in his 40s.
Sometimes you realize or forget how young he was when he was coaching in him.
But the players were absolutely in awe of him.
He had a certain personality that would evidently intimidate
people who played for him.

Milstead used to tell me that he'd be walking along the campus and see Barry Bryant walking on the sidewalk and he'd go around make a detour two or three blocks just from saying just to keep him saying hello to him.
He had that kind of personality.
Let's see were there any world events or national events that occurred while you were an undergraduate
that had an effect upon what you thought your life was going to be?
Very few.
I was active in SCONA, Student Council on National Affairs, or Student Conference on National Affairs, which I believe was started by an Aggie back about 1955 or 56, and I was active in that.
I remember John Hagler was active in it and a lot of my colleagues.
I would go pick up delegates at the train station in North Zulch.
Trains quit coming to College Station, and so...
The highlight I remember in terms of a national figure was Hubert Humphrey spoke there one time.
I don't recall anybody else of national or international note during my four years at A&M.
It's kind of an anecdote.
I remember going down to the Bush Library opening just a few months ago.
I guess what, 1998.
And seeing all these world figures like Valesa, John Major,

on and on and on all the living presidents except president reagan all the living first ladies and i told some of the cadet seniors how fortunate they were to be at a m such a monumental event regardless of your politics a presidential library is really something big we'll all remember that day but i was just kind of jokingly told one of the cadet seniors who i think a ross volunteer who was right in the middle of all this i said i hope you appreciate
the national and international figures you have when you're on the campus.
When I was at A&M, all we had was one drunk ex-county commissioner, and that was a highlight of my career.
We all kind of laughed at that, but it was a cataclysmic event.

And presidential libraries, of course, living here in Austin and being active with the LBJ Library here and now the Bush Library, it just attracts scholars and historians, and it's a wonderful advantage for any university to have that affiliation with a presidential library.
It's beyond description.
Court trips.
Where did y'all go on court trips and describe what they were like for a student?
Court trips were strictly limited to three cities in my tenure there.
Fort Worth, Dallas, and, I'm sorry, four.
Fort Worth, Dallas, Houston, and Austin.
And we would alternate.
So it would be Fort Worth, I'd be at Fort Worth and Austin one year and then Dallas and Houston the next year and then rotate back.
They were great events.
We always had
Friends who lived in one of those four towns would stay with them.
And depending on what class you were, it depends how far you had to shine your shoes and all that.
But they were highlights.
They were really great times.
Normally you'd leave College Station when?
Friday.
Come back Sunday.
Friday afternoon?
Friday afternoon.
Go do whatever partying we were going to do that night in respective towns.
Do our thing.
Go see the football game.
Come back Sunday.
Somewhat bedraggled.
And then have to start studying again Sunday night.
Now, let's see, in Austin it was Congress Avenue.
Congress Avenue.
Houston.
Houston, it was downtown Houston.
I don't remember if it was Travis.
It wasn't Main Street?
Maybe it was Main or Travis, one of those two.
Fort Worth, I don't remember.
I think it was Main Street and Fort Worth.
And Dallas, Elmer, Maine.
And Dallas was Elmer, Maine.
Right.
Do you remember any particular event of any court trip that was special to you, plus good or bad?
Saw a lot of good football players.
I remember Don Meredith was playing for SMU at the time.
Texas was starting to rebuild.
Rice was always a good team.
I know they upset us.
My senior year, the court trip, upset us.
We were number one in the nation at the time, I believe.
My junior years when, I guess, no, I'm sorry, my freshman year at Rice was when we came back and made a 21-point advantage in the last eight or nine minutes and won the game.
But SMU, TCU, Rice were all powers at that time.
So it was a big game.
Probably drew as many people then or more than we do today.
Now, normally, did you all have dates?
On court trip weekends?
Depends what your classification was.
As a freshman, it was not a freshman privilege to have a date, being facetious.
Very few of us had dates because women just didn't want to go with skinhead people.
But that changed our sophomore, junior, and senior years.
We always had dates.
Now were the Friday and Saturday night activities, were they of a positive nature?
By and large.
The parties and things like that?
Yeah.
There was excesses, but not to the point that you'd really get in trouble.
All right, now let's go to a home football weekend.
Make believe that I know nothing about what that was like.
Describe for me what went on on campus the whole weekend of a home game.
The routine was fixed.
The times and the dates and the fringe had changed.
But the routine was fixed.
And that is, Friday night, you would have a midnight yoke practice.
Saturday, you'd spend your time getting ready for the march in, and then the march in, and then the game.
And then Saturday night, you'd have individual parties.
Sometimes you would have a senior ring dance or a sophomore ball or a freshman ball coincident with a home football game.
But the routine was pretty well fixed, but it was always a lot of fun.
Now, where was Yale practices held in those days?
Yale practices were normally at the Grove.
At the Grove.
Yeah, it was not at the football stadium.
And was everything on the ground?
Did anybody get up in any kind of bleacher or riser or anything?
No, the coach.
Normally the football players would not.
talk it was the head Yale leader and the coach.
That'd be about the only people that would see it at the Yale practice but it was integral.
Right and what all what all happened?
Well it was just the Yale leaders kind of took control of it and the coach would come up depending who it was.
Bear Bryant was always pretty good at that at that deal.
I think Jim Myers was there.
My last two years, he was pretty effective.
He was more effective at Yale practice than he was the next day.
It was pretty good, too.
Go through all the Yales in spirit.
Final review.
Talk about final review for you.
Final review, it's kind of interesting because it was a very big transition.
My final review was rained out.
I'll never forget that.
So after graduation, it was pouring down rain, so I didn't get to go through with my new lieutenant bars and final review, but certainly the other three years we did.
All right.
So in your case, where were those bars pinned on?
On the collar.
No, no, no, no.
Who pinned them on?
Yeah.
It depends.
You know, it depends.
In my case, it depends on the individual.
It could have been your mother or your girlfriend or your ex-wife or ex-girlfriend.
But in my case, it was my future wife at Pindamon, who I was dating at the time.
And so where did that happen?
In this case, it was normally on the drill field.
But in this case, it was in G. Raleigh White.
Right after commencement?
After commencement and after the commissioning ceremony.
And commencement was held when?
Well, there was a commissioning ceremony, which I believe was after commencement at that time.
It was held in G. Raleigh, and at that time we had about 7,000 students on the campus, so we had easy accommodations for that.
I think there was just one graduation.
I think that's correct.
Describe commencement then.
You know, I don't remember commencement too much about it.
It's kind of

Interesting, I heard a politician one time, when I was in the Association of Former Students, give a commencement address, and he said, he was talking to all the parents, he said, you probably don't remember any commencement address you've ever heard, and this will be consistent with that.
For some reason, you just don't remember commencement addresses.
The only one I guess I remember was one of my nephews graduating from Dartmouth.
And the commencement address,
was very good, and I guess I was more receptive as an adult than I was as a graduating senior.
Did you have family there who all was at commencement?
Family was always at commencement, all my family and my grandfather and grandmother.
Silver Taps.
Make believe that I'm not an Aggie.
Tell me what Saps is and what it meant to you.
Fortunately, we didn't have too many of them when I was in school.
That's when the Ross Volunteers
It gives a salute to those who have been, who have deceased.
Normally happened at night.
It was on the campus.
I was a member of the firing squad in Ross Volunteers my junior year.
So I participated just as a member of the Ross Volunteers.
Tell me what that.
Ross Volunteers is a.
No, no, the firing squad.
Tell me what that meant.
Well, it was kind of a salute, a military salute.
Taps was played.
And you would have three platoons of the Ross Volunteers, and we would fire those fire blanks, and it would be three volleys.
I think it was, as I recall, it was three volleys of seven rifles each, so it would be 21 shots fired.
And you all would gather where?
Out in front of the old main.
But did y'all march over there?
We would march over there as Ross Volunteers.
Now, the student body would just walk over there.
Yeah, yeah.
But y'all marched.
We would march.
We would form up in front of one of the arms and march over there.
Three platoons of seven each.
In our Ross Volunteers.
In your RVs.
And did y'all take that, was that a serious event?
Very serious.
When the civil taps was over, what happened?
You just quietly go back to your rooms.
It was very quiet.
Everything just, it was quiet and you just go back to your rooms.
Do you remember ever anybody trying to act silly after a... No, no.
And what if I had, what if you or somebody else had a real big test the next day and you really had to study some more that night?
Did anybody ever do that?
Yeah, you would go back...
The protocol was basically you go back and go to bed because it's pretty late, but it was not unheard of to go ahead and turn the light on and study after silver taps.
I think that was just kind of the practical reality of it.
What were the no-no's after silver taps?
Well, first the no-no was not to go.
There was just no hell raising or anything, just a very quiet, somber kind of thing.
You go back and
Now, there might have been a light restriction, which you could pull your shutters down or something like that and study.
I don't recall any prohibition on that.
All right.
Then Muster.
Muster, of course, once a year.
Held where?
San Jacinto Day, 21st of April.
Held where?
Muster was held out in front of MSC, Memorial Student Center, when I was there.
I think that letter changed over to G. Wally White.
It would go to G. Wally White, I believe, if it was raining, but I don't recall any.
It was.
When I was there, muster was always held on the campus out in front on the lawn of the Memorial Student Center.
And about what time of day?
As I recall, it was in the afternoon.
Or it was the daytime.
It was not evening ceremony.
And did that seem to you to be an important tradition event?
Oh, certainly.
Certainly.
Yeah, we were fully indoctrinated and inculcated on muster from the time we hit the campus.
All right.
As you were preparing, approaching graduation,
What sort of world did you think you were entering?
Kind of interesting.
We had a big advantage then, and then our futures for the next two years, six months to two years, were already prescribed.
That is, we had to go to the military.
Military was obligatory at that time for all men.
And so we had, of course, had our contracts, and then we had our commissions.
So we would go in at different times.
The beauty of that is that it was a perfect transition.
certainly in a time of peace like we were in at that time.
Perfect transition from college life to professional life.
Gave you time to see different parts of the world, to mature out, to make new friends, to get integrated into men from other universities, different parts of the country.
Most Aggies were pretty provincial when we left A&M after our senior year, weren't world travel.
And this was a great maturing time, and it was for me.
Just had the time of my life when I was in service.
How well prepared did you think you were for whatever future life there was?
I had no yardstick.
I felt like, you know, when you're a senior and you go through the Corps for four years and you get out with an engineering degree, I felt like I was prepared for anything.
But there was probably a tad of insecurity there when you get right down to it.
You've been in universities, so you understand that.
But when I got in the service and I was integrated into people from

MIT and Lafayette and New York City College and some of the Ivy League schools, I felt even more prepared because I felt like we were probably matured out and had as good an education and felt better than a lot of my colleagues from other universities.
I really felt that way.
Why did you major in engineering?
Interesting story.
I'll make a long story short.
My dad was a farmer.
I come from about three generations of agriculture up in Panhandle, Texas.
And if you remember the 1950s, the cattle market broke and went through a severe drought.
And I saw my dad slowly go broke.
My good friend at that time in high school, his father was a consulting engineer.
So I just thought that was kind of a neat thing to do.
I had no idea what engineers did.
I didn't have the slightest idea.
So I went to him and said, Mr. Hazy, his name was H-A-S-I-E, Mr. Hazy, I-A-L.
I think I want to be a consulting engineer.
Tell me what to do.
He said, I'll tell you what to do.
He said, you go to Texas A&M and get a civil engineering degree.
Then you go to the service and get that behind you.
And then come back to Fort Worth and work for the Corps of Engineers and go through the training program.
You're going to learn a lot about building dams and roads and surveying and all of that.
And then finish our training program and come to work for me at Lubbock.
and come up through the ranks of my consulting firm, which seemed like a great career path.
So he was my first mentor, and I did 100% of that.

Went to E&M, got my civil engineering degree, went to the service, got that out of the way, went to the Corps of Engineers in Fort Worth, and got a great training program there, went to work for him, then he passed away.
So that disrupted my timetable, and that's what sent me back to graduate school.
But he was my first mentor, and that's kind of how I got in, made the transition first in my family, since, or last, to get out of agriculture and into a technical field.
Who were the people at A&M that helped shape your life there?
I may have addressed some of that before in my earlier tape, but certainly I had some great mentors.
Doc Harrington was my hydraulics professor who revered.
He was just great.
A fellow named Dr. Nederman was my reinforced concrete.
Professor, he was... That's Wendell Nederman.
Wendell Nederman, outstanding, one of the best professors I ever had.
Certainly Spencer Buchanan, soil mechanics.
Those are the three that I really revered.
And, of course, in graduate school, I had even more mentors.
Graduate school is a little bit different.
In the College of Engineering, I had some just absolutely marvelous professors here at the University of Texas in the 60s.
So the foundation I had from those three gentlemen that I just mentioned, plus two professors in particular here at Texas, gave me opportunities I would never have had had I not met them.
Were there some NM advisor, counselor, role model people other than faculty who were important to your future?
MSC, core, anything like that?
Not really.
The only one was the director of MSC at that time.
I think I may have mentioned him too, Wayne Stark.
Talk about him.
Wayne Stark was probably the only non-professor mentor that I had, and I didn't flange in quite as much with Wayne.
He knew my older brother who had gone to A&M.
He knew my family, so he made it a point to know me, as he did many students on the campus.
But I think he was probably more involved in perpetuating
students to go to Harvard Business School who were in the business side of it, and not necessarily just engineers.
But he was a one-in-a-million kind of guy.
He built up the MSC.
He was a Mackville thinker, a deep thinker, and had files on every student in the world.
I'd go to him, even when I became president of the Association of Former Students, I'd go to Wayne and ask about some student or former student, and he'd have a file on them.
He had copious files on his people that he helped.
Describe the Aggie bonfire in your student days.
It was controversial, believe it or not.
A lot of the professors who had come to A&M from other universities thought it was a waste of time and encroached on study time, but of course that was not negotiable.
We had one week for bonfire.
Everybody had to work on just bonfire week.
We started one week before.
Everything we could do was done in one week.
It always rained.
We had cutting areas.
It was great camaraderie.
We tried to get a little studying done during that week, but it was very difficult to do.
But Bonfire Week was... Where was it built?
It was built, I believe, all four years when I was at A&M.
It was built to where it continued to be built for many, many years thereafter, and that's behind Duncan Meshall over by what's now the A&M Press.
So that was our, it used to be, before I got to A&M, I know it was on the drill field, but then they moved it.
And what was in the bonfire?
What was it that was burned up?
What was it made of?
It was made of logs, mostly hardwood.
I guess all hardwood from Prattis Bottoms.
Farmers out there would be glad to have you come out and clear some of their land.
It was no value with the timber on it.
But no trash?
Oh, no.
No, that went out many years ago.
I think it was strictly a log bonfire.
I can remember certainly since the 40s probably.
And what was always on top of it?
The outhouse, of course, and an Austin City Limits sign.
And where did the outhouse come from?
You know, I'm not sure I can answer that.
Various places.
I think they would construct them or they would steal it or whatever.
It was normally stolen from some place.
I've often wondered sometimes was it just made just for that purpose?
Probably was.
I don't have a recollection of that.
If they could find one, they'd steal it.
If not, they'd just make one.
But the one thing they would steal in violation of state law was the City of Austin City Limits sign.
I have to admit, I think as my junior year, I helped perpetuate that crime.
I think at some point after I got out of school, they caught some kids doing that.
Again, you're stealing from the state, so it's a fun thing to do, but it's certainly illegal.
Now, during your days, did anybody kidnap a mascot from another school?
I don't believe that happened.
It was very common.
Actually, after I left, it was probably more common, and before I got there, it was common.
When I was there, I don't recall that ever happening.
Because it has happened and then not happened for a while.
Yeah.
Let's see.
How were diversity of student body?
How were Hispanic students at A&M treated?
The same as all of us.
About the only minority group we had there were Hispanics.
But most of the Hispanics came from the border, from Laredo.
I'm not talking about the international Latin, ethnically Latin people.
I'm talking about the Hispanics, Mexican Americans.
No, they were absolutely no different.
And were there any Asian students in the Corps, Asian American?
Probably were, but you could probably count them on one hand at that time.
Ironically, I remember one of the finest football players in my dad's day was a Japanese American.
So they have a long history of going to A&M.
Was that Kishi?
Kishi, yeah.
From Orange County.
I didn't know that, but I remember looking at him and my dad talking about him all the time.
My dad was a class of 26.
And one of the elder members of that family was confined early in World War II because his hobby was ham radio operating.
No, I'd be darned.
And they thought, of course, he must be spying.
Then they found that...
